GenericProxyHandler does not always send the correct data when
forwarding requests. self.data_bytes is not properly cleaned up on all
request types.

- DELETE, HEAD and OPTIONS requests

bd92399b8c4b54d1d4982d42fb56ae87d154ef01.message:
DynamoDBStreams Now Returns Valid ShardIDs. (#403)

* DynamoDBStreams Now Returns Valid ShardIDs.

ShardIDs returned from the DynamoDBStreams emulator now mimic ShardIDs
in the production service.  Namely, they comply with the length requirements
in botocore.  Each returned ShardID is > 28 characters in length.

As ShardIDs from Kinesis are appended with `-$UUID5`.  The UUID5 value
generated is relative to the Kinesis stream name as well as the Kinesis
ShardID, ensuring that the value is consistent across multiple calls to
`describe_stream`.  Before ShardID values are passed through to
Kinesis, they are unwrapped to the original Kinesis value.

460fe7939291c833af6cfae4e9205a27ce744cb2.summary: Instead of trying to set the default content-type on GET, set it on PUT (#589)
460fe7939291c833af6cfae4e9205a27ce744cb2.message:
Instead of trying to set the default content-type on GET, set it on PUT (#589)

According to https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/API/RESTObjectPUT.html
, if there is a PUT without a content-type, 'binary/octet-stream' will be used
as the default.

This changes the previous attempt at fixing this default, which was just setting
the content-type for GET's, which would override the content type of the
uploaded file, rather then respect the original uploaded content-type, like it
should have.

9832ee67163bead2c899044be0682dedba687044.summary: Add Filter Policy Support To Sns Subscriptions (#674)
9832ee67163bead2c899044be0682dedba687044.message:
Add Filter Policy Support To Sns Subscriptions (#674)

See: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/message-filtering.html

This commit adds filter policy support for SNS subscriptions. Filter
policies are set on the subscription and help filter the messages that
that subscription is interested in. If a message does not contain the
appropriate message attributes to pass the filter check, then the
message is not relayed to the subscriber. If the message does pass the
filter check then the message is passed to the subscriber.

bdd79e282afb1b52203d6bc09ba9c66f590c003e.summary: fix SQS->Lambda when setup with api gateway (#1636)
bdd79e282afb1b52203d6bc09ba9c66f590c003e.message:
fix SQS->Lambda when setup with api gateway (#1636)

As described in this issue https://github.com/localstack/localstack/issues/1596 by @vballa
whenever an SQS -> Lambda is triggered by previously it was erroring in
the md5 hashing. The reason for this was that there was no "data" body
for GET requests meaning that data in localstack/services/sqs/sqs_listener.py#_send_message was None and therefore throwing an exception.

We could have fixed it by remapping the query params in the forward_request however
it felt more natural that this should correctly be a POST request
passing the data through.

This added an additional test, which when reverted to original setup
correctly errors because the original spec missed adding an event_source
and lambda for the sqs -> lambda flows. I kept the original test as it
also provides value in itself as well

9770dc75074043909ce373902cc1b6fa54560b56.summary: Fix: SES not emitting SNS messages (#7207)
9770dc75074043909ce373902cc1b6fa54560b56.message:
Fix: SES not emitting SNS messages (#7207)

* feat: implement sns -> ses event emitting

This test sets up a verified email, connects an SNS topic to SES and sends an
email. To test this, the test connects an SQS queue to the SNS topic to
ensure the messages have been received correctly.

We use the new `sqs_receive_num_messages` fixture from the previous
commit to receive the required three messages:

1. SES sends a test message to the topic when the configuration set is
   connected
2. SES sends a "sent" event
3. SES sends a "delivered" event

See #7184

* fix: get sns client for region and account

* fix: rename fixture to emphasise SNS destination

Track additional host variables (#7883)

These variables are
* `LOCALSTACK_HOSTNAME` which is not _meant_ to be settable by the user
  as it's used internally, but it is settable
* `LOCALSTACK_HOST` which is a new variable that we plan to use in
  exchange for `HOSTNAME_EXTERNAL` and `LOCALSTACK_HOSTNAME`.

These variables are added so that we can use the analytics to see the
usage of the previous variables drop.

02c9b8ff2d0e6c38ae6f32f5dd44fdd33f4c4f99.message:
Configure cosmetic and functional variables with LOCALSTACK_HOST and GATEWAY_LISTEN (#7893)

Switch to using `LOCALSTACK_HOST` and `GATEWAY_LISTEN` for configuring
the cosmetic and functional properties of LocalStack.

* `LOCALSTACK_HOST`: cosmetic - interpolated into URLs and hostnames/ports
returned
* `GATEWAY_LISTEN`: functional - replaces `EDGE_PORT`, `EDGE_PORT_HTTP`,
  `EDGE_BIND_HOST`.

d80b76a0de459fe728a175dce664c5bcc93c6a60.message:
Detect containerd containers (#8071)

Check for marker files left by our Dockerfile first, but otherwise check
for the mount filesystem type as containerd does not leave any obvious
marker file around (e.g. `/.dockerenv`).

Note: macos has a beta option to use containerd for managing images, and
this change detects this case as well.

b2cc972824d9c77ea15364908650568ad1070b31.summary: Fix containerd detection for host mode (#8112)
b2cc972824d9c77ea15364908650568ad1070b31.message:
Fix containerd detection for host mode (#8112)

Previously, if _any_ containerd container was running on the host, and
LocalStack was started in host mode then it would detect the
`containerd` string in the disk partitions, and return True. This is not
a great default for host mode, as it binds LocalStack to 0.0.0.0.

This change searches through the `/proc/mounts` virtual file
system looking for mount options that include `containerd`. This means
that only the root mount point is considered, rather than any host
mounts that correspond to other containers. After this update, while
running a containerd container in the background and starting LocalStack
in host mode, the docker status is correctly determined to be False, and
LocalStack is bound to 127.0.0.1.

Introduce a deployment abstraction over the legacy generic base models,
and the new resource providers, and integrate with the new resource
provider deployment mechanism: `ResourceProviderExecutor`. This change
does not affect current behaviour as the new resource providers are
disabled unless the `CFN_RESOURCE_PROVIDERS_V2` flag is enabled.
